# Backend rules

# Frontend rules

- You're an expert frontend developer
- You write code that is clean, readable, and maintainable. 
- You don't over-engineer solutions. You write simple code that works and is easy to understand.
- You follow best practices and keep the UI consistent. 
- You care about UI details and strive to make the product look and feel great. 

## General guidelines

- Use typescript and Next.js
- Use react-query for data fetching, caching and mutations
- Use react-hook-form for form handling
- Use tailwind for styling. Look at /packages/tailwind-config for reference
- Use our design system for components. Look at /packages/ui for reference.
- When using a type from the backend, make sure to use from /packages/request-types
- Avoid using @onefootprint/types - it's deprecated and will be removed in the future


## Data fetching
- When using react-query and integrating with the backend, use the queries from /packages/axios. If you're using from the dashboard app,
you'll likely need to import from @onefootprint/axios/dashboard
- Ideally, split the result into a ErrorComponent, LoadingComponent and ContentComponent:

Data fetching:

```tsx
import { getEntitiesByFpIdBusinessOwnersOptions } from '@onefootprint/axios/dashboard';
import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';

const App = () => {
  const { isPending, error, data } = useQuery(
    getEntitiesByFpIdBusinessOwnersOptions({
      path: { fpId: entity.id },
    }),
  );
  if (isPending) {
    return <Loading />;
  }
  if (error) {
    return <ErrorComponent error={error} />;
  }
  return <Content data={data} />;
};
```

Mutations:
- When using mutations, make sure to handle errors. In most of the situations, you'll want to use useRequestErrorToast hook.

```tsx
import { postEntitiesByFpIdBusinessOwnersKycLinksMutation } from '@onefootprint/axios/dashboard';
import { useMutation } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { useRequestErrorToast } from '@onefootprint/hooks';

const App = () => {
  const mutation = useMutation(postEntitiesByFpIdBusinessOwnersKycLinksMutation());
  const showRequestErrorToast = useRequestErrorToast();

  const handleSubmit = async () => {
    try {
      await mutation.mutateAsync({ path: { fpId }, body: {} });
    } catch (error) {
      showRequestErrorToast(error)
    }
  };
};
```

## Forms
- When using react-hook-form, make sure to always type the form data:

```tsx
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';

type FormData = {
  name: string;
};

const App = () => {
  const formMethods = useForm<FormData>();
  ...
};
```

- When you need to conditionally render a field based on another field's value, use the `useWatch` hook (and not the `watch` function):

```tsx
import { useForm, useWatch } from 'react-hook-form';

const App = () => {
  const { control } = useForm();
  const watchName = useWatch({ control: control, name: 'name' });
  ...
};
```

## Styling and components

- We are moving to tailwind. Look at /packages/tailwind-config for reference, however, most of the code is still written with styled-components.
- When touching a code, feel free to convert it to tailwind.

### Guidelines
- We use a lot of Box / Stack components from our design system. These components are deprecated and will be removed in the future.

This is an example:

```typescript
import { Box } from '@onefootprint/ui';

const App = () => {
  return <Box backgroundColor="primary" color="secondary" borderRadius="default" borderWidth={1} borderStyle="solid" borderColor="primary" marginBottom={4} justifyContent="center">...</Box>
};
```

In order to migrate Box components to Tailwind, follow these guidelines:

#### Basic Properties:
- Box components are replaced with a standard `div` element
- `backgroundColor` -> `bg-{color}` (e.g., `bg-primary`)
- `color` -> `text-{color}` (e.g., `text-secondary`)

#### Border Properties:
- Use combined classes: `border border-solid border-{color}`
- Border radius: 
  - Default: `rounded`
  - Other sizes: `rounded-xl`

#### Spacing Scale (in pixels):
| Size | Padding     | Margin      | Gap         |
|------|------------|-------------|-------------|
| 0    | p-0        | m-0         | gap-0       |
| 1    | p-0.5 (2)  | m-0.5       | gap-0.5     |
| 2    | p-1 (4)    | m-1         | gap-1       |
| 3    | p-2 (8)    | m-2         | gap-2       |
| 4    | p-3 (12)   | m-3         | gap-3       |
| 5    | p-4 (16)   | m-4         | gap-4       |
| 6    | p-5 (20)   | m-5         | gap-5       |
| 7    | p-6 (24)   | m-6         | gap-6       |
| 8    | p-8 (32)   | m-8         | gap-8       |
| 9    | p-10 (40)  | m-10        | gap-10      |
| 10   | p-16 (64)  | m-16        | gap-16      |
| 11   | p-24 (96)  | m-24        | gap-24      |
| 12   | p-32 (128) | m-32        | gap-32      |
| 13   | p-40 (156) | m-40        | gap-40      |
| 14   | p-48 (192) | m-48        | gap-48      |
| 15   | p-64 (256) | m-64        | gap-64      |

#### Common Box Props to Tailwind Classes:
- alignItems="center" -> items-center
- justifyContent="center" -> justify-center
- alignContent="center" -> content-center
- flexWrap="wrap" -> flex-wrap
- flexDirection="column" -> flex-col
- gap={4} -> gap-3
- width="100%" -> w-full
- height="100%" -> h-full

#### Stack Component:
The Stack component is a specialized Box with flex display. Convert it as follows:
- <Stack> -> <div className="flex">
- <Stack center> -> <div className="flex items-center justify-center">
- <Stack direction="column"> -> <div className="flex flex-col">
- <Stack gap={4}> -> <div className="flex gap-4">

#### Text Component:
The Text component maps directly to HTML elements with Tailwind classes:
- <Text variant="body-1" color="secondary"> -> <p className="text-body-1 text-secondary">


#### Use cx to add conditional styles:

```typescript
import { cx } from 'class-variance-authority';

const className = cx('text-label-3 truncate group-hover:text-accent', {
  'text-accent': selected.id === playbook.id,
  'text-primary': selected.id !== playbook.id,
});
```

### Use cva to create component variants:

```typescript
import { type VariantProps, cva } from 'class-variance-authority';
import type { HTMLAttributes } from 'react';

export type BadgeProps = HTMLAttributes<HTMLSpanElement> & VariantProps<typeof badge>;

const Badge = ({ children, className, variant, ...props }: BadgeProps) => {
  return (
    <span className={badge({ variant, className })} {...props}>
      {children}
    </span>
  );
};

const badge = cva(['inline-flex items-center justify-center', 'text-caption-1', 'rounded-lg', 'px-2 py-1'], {
  variants: {
    variant: {
      accent: ['text-accent', 'bg-accent'],
      error: ['text-error', 'bg-error'],
      info: ['text-info', 'bg-info'],
  },
  defaultVariants: {
    variant: 'neutral',
  },
});
```

## Tests

We have 3 kinds of tests:
- Unit tests - using jest and react-testing-library
- Interactive tests - using storybook and vitest
- E2E tests, using playwright

Most of the time, you should write unit and interactive tests. 

### General guidelines for tests
- Prefer to write tests that are focused on the user's perspective and actions they would take.
- Use this pattern to write tests:

```typescript
describe('when something happens', () => {
  it('should do something', () => {
    ...
  })
})
```

- If you need a fixture, use from `@onefootprint/fixtures`. If you're in the dashboard app, use from `@onefootprint/fixtures/dashboard`.
- Name it as the fixture name + 'Fixture' (Always ending with Fixture)

```typescript
import { getOnboardingConfiguration } from '@onefootprint/fixtures/dashboard';

const onboardingConfigFixture = getOnboardingConfiguration({ name: 'Identity verification' });

```

### React testing library guidelines
- Use find* any time you want to query for something that may not be available right away. Avoid using `waitFor` when possible.
- Avoid having multiple assertions in a single waitFor callback
- Write using semantical roles - avoid using `getByTestId` and prefer `getByRole`
- Do not use cleanup after each test - jest does this for you
- Use userEvent for all interactions, instead of fireEvent

### Unit tests
- Use @onefootprint/testing-utils for importing anything related to tests

```typescript
import { customRender, screen, waitFor, userEvent } from '@onefootprint/testing-utils';
```


